{"title_page": "Morgan Klimchuk", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Morgan Klimchuk\n| image = Morgan Klimchuk.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|03|02}}\n| birth_place = [[Regina, Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 7\n| weight_lb = 235\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left wing]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league= [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| team = [[Ottawa Senators]]\n| prospect_team = [[Belleville Senators]]\n| prospect_league = [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| former_teams = [[Calgary Flames]]\n| draft = 28th overall\n| draft_year = 2013\n| draft_team = [[Calgary Flames]]\n| career_start = 2014\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Morgan Klimchuk''' (born March 2, 1995) is a [[Ukrainian Canadians|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|winger]] for the [[Belleville Senators]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) while under contract to the [[Ottawa Senators]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). Klimchuk was selected in the first round, 28th overall, at the [[2013 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Calgary Flames]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] in family with [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] roots, Klimchuk grew up in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], and played his [[minor hockey]] in the Calgary Buffaloes system.<ref name=\"DraftProfile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/draftprospectdetail.htm?dpid=82149 |title=Morgan Klimchuk draft profile |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> He was the [[captain (ice hockey)|captain]] of his team in the [[Alberta Major Bantam Hockey League]] in 2009\u201310 and led his squad to the final of the Western Canadian Bantam championship, ultimately settling for second place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whl.ca/article/regina-pats-sign-first-pick-in-2010-bantam-draft-klimchuk |title=Regina Pats sign first pick in 2010 Bantam Draft |publisher=Western Hockey League |date=May 31, 2010 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> The [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL)'s [[Regina Pats]] selected him in the first round, fifth overall, at the 2010 WHL Bantam Draft,<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Flett |editor-first=Cory |editor-last2=Watts |editor-first2=Jesse |title=2012\u201313 WHL Official Guide |publisher=Western Hockey League |year=2012 |page=110}}</ref> and he appeared in five games with the Pats in [[2010\u201311 WHL season|2010\u201311]].<ref name=\"WHLProfile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.whl.ca/roster/show/id/8318 |title=Morgan Klimchuk profile |publisher=Western Hockey League |accessdate=July 1, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707113941/http://www.whl.ca/roster/show/id/8318 |archivedate=July 7, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Klimchuk joined the Pats full-time in [[2011\u201312 WHL season|2011\u201312]]. He played in 67 games, and his 36 points helped Regina reach the WHL playoffs for the first time since 2008.<ref>{{cite web |last=Watts |first=Jesse |url=http://www.whl.ca/article/catching-up-with-morgan-klimchuk |title=Catching up with... Morgan Klimchuk |publisher=Western Hockey League |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> He was a member of Team Pacific at the [[2012 World U-17 Hockey Challenge]], finishing second in team scoring with six points in six games, and played with Team Alberta at the 2011 [[Canada Winter Games]].<ref name=\"DraftProfile\" /> \n\nIn his second WHL season, [[2012\u201313 WHL season|2012\u201313]], Klimchuk improved to 76 points and finished second in team scoring.<ref>{{cite web |last=Peterson |first=Torie |url=http://flames.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=676025 |title=Numerology: Morkan Klimchuk |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |date=July 1, 2013 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> He made two appearances with the [[Canada men's national under-18 ice hockey team|Canadian national under-18 team]]. He was a member of the gold medal-winning Canadian team at the [[2012 Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament]]. Playing on the [[line (ice hockey)|top line]] with [[Sam Reinhart]] and [[Connor McDavid]], Klimchuk scored eight points to help lead Canada to a gold medal at the [[2013 IIHF World U18 Championships]].<ref name=\"DraftProfile\" />\n\nPlaying all roles in Regina, Klimchuk developed into a top prospect for the [[2013 NHL Entry Draft]] and was ranked by the [[NHL Central Scouting Bureau]] 25th among North American skaters. He credited the chance to play in all offensive and defensive situations with helping him develop a strong two-way game.<ref name=\"CHDraft\">{{cite news |last=Cruickshank |first=Scott |title=Klimchuk always fond of Flames |work=Calgary Herald |date=July 1, 2013 |page=C3}}</ref> The [[Calgary Flames]] used the pick they acquired in the [[Jarome Iginla]] trade to select Klimchuk in the first round, 28th overall.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sportak |first=Randy |title=Pressure on Poirier, Klimchuk |work=Calgary Sun |date=July 1, 2013 |page=S5}}</ref> He signed a three-year entry-level contract with the Flames on December 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Flames sign Morgan Klimchuk|url=https://www.nhl.com/flames/news/flames-sign-morgan-klimchuk/c-696405|website=NHL.com|accessdate=May 11, 2018|date=December 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn January 2, 2015, Klimchuk was dealt from the Pats to the [[Brandon Wheat Kings]], in a trade that saw Jesse Gabrielle move to the Pats.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHEAT KINGS ACQUIRE KLIMCHUK|url=http://wheatkings.com/wheat-kings-acquire-klimchuk/|website=wheatkings.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nKlimchuk was invited to the Flames' 2015 training camp, but was assigned to the Flames [[American Hockey League|AHL]] affiliate, the [[Stockton Heat]] for the [[2015\u201316 AHL season|2015\u201316 season]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kisker|first1=Brandon|title=Flames Make Training Camp Assignments|url=http://stocktonheat.com/news/flames-make-training-camp-assignments/|website=stocktonheat.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=September 27, 2015}}</ref> Klimchuk made his NHL debut on February 19, 2018, against the [[Boston Bruins]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=George|title=NHL DEBUT A LEARNING EXPERIENCE FOR KLIMCHUK|url=https://www.nhl.com/flames/news/nhl-debut-a-learning-experience-for-klimchuk/c-296143426|website=NHL.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> The following day he was reassigned to the AHL.<ref>{{cite web|title=Flames assign Morgan Klimchuk to AHL Stockton|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/flames-assign-morgan-klimchuk-ahl-stockton/|website=sportsnet.ca|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=February 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018\u201319 AHL season|2018\u201319]] season, on November 27, 2018, Klimchuk was traded by the Flames to the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] in exchange for [[Andrew Nielsen (ice hockey)|Andrew Nielsen]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Maple Leafs Acquire Klimchuk From Calgary |url=https://www.nhl.com/mapleleafs/news/leafs-acquie-klimchuk/c-302368174 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> Klimchuk appeared in just 13 games with the [[Toronto Marlies]], before he was traded by the Maple Leafs for the second time within the season to the [[Ottawa Senators]] in exchange for [[Gabriel Gagne]] on January 11, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leafs send Klimchuk to Senators for Gagne |url=https://www.tsn.ca/leafs-send-klimchuk-to-senators-for-gagne-1.1239857 |website= [[The Sports Network]] |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! 