 title = [[List of Calgary Flames draft picks|Calgary Flames first round draft pick]] | years = [[2013 NHL Entry Draft|2013]] | after = [[Sam Bennett (ice hockey)|Sam Bennett]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klimchuk, Morgan}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Abbotsford Heat players]]\n[[Category:Belleville Senators players]]\n[[Category:Brandon Wheat Kings players]]\n[[Category:Calgary Flames draft picks]]\n[[Category:Calgary Flames players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate ice hockey players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey left wingers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Alberta]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League first round draft picks]]\n[[Category:Regina Pats players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Regina, Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Stockton Heat players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Marlies players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Morgan Klimchuk\n| image = Morgan Klimchuk.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|03|02}}\n| birth_place = [[Regina, Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 0\n| weight_lb = 185\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Left wing]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league= [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| team = [[Ottawa Senators]]\n| prospect_team = [[Belleville Senators]]\n| prospect_league = [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| former_teams = [[Calgary Flames]]\n| draft = 28th overall\n| draft_year = 2013\n| draft_team = [[Calgary Flames]]\n| career_start = 2014\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Morgan Klimchuk''' (born March 2, 1995) is a [[Ukrainian Canadians|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|winger]] for the [[Belleville Senators]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) while under contract to the [[Ottawa Senators]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). Klimchuk was selected in the first round, 28th overall, at the [[2013 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Calgary Flames]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] in family with [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] roots, Klimchuk grew up in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], and played his [[minor hockey]] in the Calgary Buffaloes system.<ref name=\"DraftProfile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/draftprospectdetail.htm?dpid=82149 |title=Morgan Klimchuk draft profile |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> He was the [[captain (ice hockey)|captain]] of his team in the [[Alberta Major Bantam Hockey League]] in 2009\u201310 and led his squad to the final of the Western Canadian Bantam championship, ultimately settling for second place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whl.ca/article/regina-pats-sign-first-pick-in-2010-bantam-draft-klimchuk |title=Regina Pats sign first pick in 2010 Bantam Draft |publisher=Western Hockey League |date=May 31, 2010 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> The [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL)'s [[Regina Pats]] selected him in the first round, fifth overall, at the 2010 WHL Bantam Draft,<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Flett |editor-first=Cory |editor-last2=Watts |editor-first2=Jesse |title=2012\u201313 WHL Official Guide |publisher=Western Hockey League |year=2012 |page=110}}</ref> and he appeared in five games with the Pats in [[2010\u201311 WHL season|2010\u201311]].<ref name=\"WHLProfile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.whl.ca/roster/show/id/8318 |title=Morgan Klimchuk profile |publisher=Western Hockey League |accessdate=July 1, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707113941/http://www.whl.ca/roster/show/id/8318 |archivedate=July 7, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Klimchuk joined the Pats full-time in [[2011\u201312 WHL season|2011\u201312]]. He played in 67 games, and his 36 points helped Regina reach the WHL playoffs for the first time since 2008.<ref>{{cite web |last=Watts |first=Jesse |url=http://www.whl.ca/article/catching-up-with-morgan-klimchuk |title=Catching up with... Morgan Klimchuk |publisher=Western Hockey League |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> He was a member of Team Pacific at the [[2012 World U-17 Hockey Challenge]], finishing second in team scoring with six points in six games, and played with Team Alberta at the 2011 [[Canada Winter Games]].<ref name=\"DraftProfile\" /> \n\nIn his second WHL season, [[2012\u201313 WHL season|2012\u201313]], Klimchuk improved to 76 points and finished second in team scoring.<ref>{{cite web |last=Peterson |first=Torie |url=http://flames.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=676025 |title=Numerology: Morkan Klimchuk |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |date=July 1, 2013 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> He made two appearances with the [[Canada men's national under-18 ice hockey team|Canadian national under-18 team]]. He was a member of the gold medal-winning Canadian team at the [[2012 Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament]]. Playing on the [[line (ice hockey)|top line]] with [[Sam Reinhart]] and [[Connor McDavid]], Klimchuk scored eight points to help lead Canada to a gold medal at the [[2013 IIHF World U18 Championships]].<ref name=\"DraftProfile\" />\n\nPlaying all roles in Regina, Klimchuk developed into a top prospect for the [[2013 NHL Entry Draft]] and was ranked by the [[NHL Central Scouting Bureau]] 25th among North American skaters. He credited the chance to play in all offensive and defensive situations with helping him develop a strong two-way game.<ref name=\"CHDraft\">{{cite news |last=Cruickshank |first=Scott |title=Klimchuk always fond of Flames |work=Calgary Herald |date=July 1, 2013 |page=C3}}</ref> The [[Calgary Flames]] used the pick they acquired in the [[Jarome Iginla]] trade to select Klimchuk in the first round, 28th overall.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sportak |first=Randy |title=Pressure on Poirier, Klimchuk |work=Calgary Sun |date=July 1, 2013 |page=S5}}</ref> He signed a three-year entry-level contract with the Flames on December 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Flames sign Morgan Klimchuk|url=https://www.nhl.com/flames/news/flames-sign-morgan-klimchuk/c-696405|website=NHL.com|accessdate=May 11, 2018|date=December 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn January 2, 2015, Klimchuk was dealt from the Pats to the [[Brandon Wheat Kings]], in a trade that saw Jesse Gabrielle move to the Pats.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHEAT KINGS ACQUIRE KLIMCHUK|url=http://wheatkings.com/wheat-kings-acquire-klimchuk/|website=wheatkings.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nKlimchuk was invited to the Flames' 2015 training camp, but was assigned to the Flames [[American Hockey League|AHL]] affiliate, the [[Stockton Heat]] for the [[2015\u201316 AHL season|2015\u201316 season]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kisker|first1=Brandon|title=Flames Make Training Camp Assignments|url=http://stocktonheat.com/news/flames-make-training-camp-assignments/|website=stocktonheat.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=September 27, 2015}}</ref> Klimchuk made his NHL debut on February 19, 2018, against the [[Boston Bruins]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=George|title=NHL DEBUT A LEARNING EXPERIENCE FOR KLIMCHUK|url=https://www.nhl.com/flames/news/nhl-debut-a-learning-experience-for-klimchuk/c-296143426|website=NHL.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> The following day he was reassigned to the AHL.<ref>{{cite web|title=Flames assign Morgan Klimchuk to AHL Stockton|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/flames-assign-morgan-klimchuk-ahl-stockton/|website=sportsnet.ca|accessdate=May 12, 2018|date=February 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018\u201319 AHL season|2018\u201319]] season, on November 27, 2018, Klimchuk was traded by the Flames to the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] in exchange for [[Andrew Nielsen (ice hockey)|Andrew Nielsen]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Maple Leafs Acquire Klimchuk From Calgary |url=https://www.nhl.com/mapleleafs/news/leafs-acquie-klimchuk/c-302368174 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=November 28, 2018 |date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> Klimchuk appeared in just 13 games with the [[Toronto Marlies]], before he was traded by the Maple Leafs for the second time within the season to the [[Ottawa Senators]] in exchange for [[Gabriel Gagne]] on January 11, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leafs send Klimchuk to Senators for Gagne |url=https://www.tsn.ca/leafs-send-klimchuk-to-senators-for-gagne-1.1239857 |website= [[The Sports Network]] |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| [[2010\u201311 WHL season|2010\u201311]]\n| [[Regina Pats]]\n| [[Western Hockey League|WHL]]\n| 5\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2011\u201312 WHL season|2011\u201312]]\n| Regina Pats\n| WHL\n| 67\n| 18\n| 18\n| 36\n| 27\n| 5\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n|-\n| [[2012\u201313 WHL season|2012\u201313]]\n| Regina Pats\n| WHL\n| 72\n| 36\n| 40\n| 76\n| 20\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2013\u201314 WHL season|2013\u201314]]\n| Regina Pats\n| WHL\n| 57\n| 30\n| 44\n| 74\n| 27\n| 4\n| 3\n| 2\n| 5\n| 2\n|-\n| [[2013\u201314 AHL season|2013\u201314]]\n| [[Abbotsford Heat]]\n| [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| 4\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 4\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2014\u201315 WHL season|2014\u201315]]\n| Regina Pats\n| WHL\n| 27\n| 14\n| 16\n| 30\n| 12\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 2014\u201315\n| [[Brandon Wheat Kings]]\n| WHL\n| 33\n| 20\n| 30\n| 50\n| 12\n| 13\n| 3\n| 10\n| 13\n| 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2015\u201316 AHL season|2015\u201316]]\n| [[Stockton Heat]]\n| AHL\n| 55\n| 3\n| 6\n| 9\n| 10\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[2016\u201317 AHL season|2016\u201317]]\n| Stockton Heat\n| AHL\n| 66\n| 19\n| 24\n| 43\n| 36\n| 2\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2017\u201318 AHL season|2017\u201318]]\n| Stockton Heat\n| AHL\n| 62\n| 19\n| 21\n| 40\n| 24\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318]]\n| [[Calgary Flames]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2018\u201319 AHL season|2018\u201319]]\n| Stockton Heat\n| AHL\n| 17\n| 3\n| 5\n| 8\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- \n| 2018\u201319\n| [[Toronto Marlies]]\n| AHL\n| 13\n| 2\n| 0\n| 2\n| 21\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2018\u201319\n| [[Belleville Senators]]\n| AHL\n| 8\n| 4\n| 1\n| 5\n| 4\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\"|NHL totals\n! 1\n! 0\n! 0\n! 0\n! 0\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" ID=\"Table3\" style=\"text-align:center; width:40em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! Year\n! Team\n! Event\n! Result\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| [[2013 IIHF World U18 Championships|2013]]\n| [[Canada men's national under-18 ice hockey team|Canada]]\n| [[IIHF World U18 Championship|WJC18]]\n| {{goca}}\n| 7\n| 3\n| 5\n| 8\n| 6\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=4|Junior totals\n! 7\n! 3\n! 5\n! 8\n! 6\n|}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Awards\n! Year\n! \n|-\n| [[Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament]] gold medal\n| [[2012 Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament|2012]]\n| <ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.chl.ca/article/22-chl-players-win-2012-ivan-hlinka-u18-gold | publisher = [[Canadian Hockey League]] | date = August 1, 2012 | accessdate = August 2, 2012 | title = 22 CHL players win 2012 Ivan Hlinka gold }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[IIHF World U18 Championship]] gold medal\n| [[2013 IIHF World U18 Championships|2013]]\n| <ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/news/canada-wins-u18-worlds-gold-medal | title = Canada's National Men's Under-18 Team wins gold medal at 2013 IIHF Ice Hockey U18 World Championship | publisher = [[Hockey Canada]] | date = May 6, 2013 | accessdate = May 6, 2013}}<!-- Bot generated title --></ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Ice hockey stats}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box | before = [[\u00c9mile Poirier]] | title = [[List of Calgary Flames draft picks|Calgary Flames first round draft pick]] | years = [[2013 NHL Entry Draft|2013]] | after = [[Sam Bennett (ice hockey)|Sam Bennett]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klimchuk, Morgan}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Abbotsford Heat players]]\n[[Category:Belleville Senators players]]\n[[Category:Brandon Wheat Kings players]]\n[[Category:Calgary Flames draft picks]]\n[[Category:Calgary Flames players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate ice hockey players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey left wingers]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Alberta]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League first round draft picks]]\n[[Category:Regina Pats players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Regina, Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Stockton Heat players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Marlies players]]\n", "name_user": "Super66466", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgan_Klimchuk"}
{"title_page": "Drive-by shooting", "text_new": "{{short description|Type of assault that typically involves the perpetrator firing a weapon from within a motor vehicle and then fleeing}}\n{{redirect|Drive-by}}\n{{For|the album by the Rollins Band|Drive by Shooting}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\nA '''drive-by shooting''' is a type of assault that usually involves the perpetrator's firing a weapon from within a [[motor vehicle]] and then fleeing.<ref name=\"hutson\">\n{{cite journal| last1 = Hutson | first1 = H. Range| last2 = Anglin | first2 = Deirdre| last3 = Pratts | first3 = Michael J. Jr.| title = Adolescents and Children Injured or Killed in Drive-By Shootings in Los Angeles| journal = New England Journal of Medicine| volume = 330| issue = 5| pages = 324\u2013327| doi = 10.1056/NEJM199402033300506| pmid = 8277953| date = 3 February 1994}}</ref> Drive-by shootings allow the perpetrator(s) to quickly strike their target and flee the scene before law enforcement is able to respond.\n\n==Historical conception==\n[[File:Makhno en 1918.JPG|220px|thumb|right|[[Nestor Makhno]] (pictured in 1918) is attributed with inventing the tactics of drive-by shooting using horses, long before motor vehicles became common]]\nThe invention of the drive-by shooting is attributed to [[Nestor Makhno]],<ref>William Henry Chamberlin, ''Russia's Iron Age'', Ayer Publishing, 1970, p201; V. Rapoport, Y. Alekseev, V. G. Treml (translated by B. Adams)</ref><ref>''High Treason: Essays on the History of the Red Army, 1918\u20131938'', Duke University Press, 1985, p68</ref><ref>Michael Malet, ''Nestor Makhno in the Russian Civil War'', Macmillan, 1982, p85</ref><ref>Steve Zaloga, Leland S. Ness, ''Red Army Handbook, 1939\u201345'', Sutton, 1998, p105</ref><ref>Leon Trotsky, ''How the Revolution Armed: The Military Writings and Speeches of Leon Trotsky'', New Park Publications, 1981, p 295</ref><ref>Edward R. Kantowicz, The Rage of Nations: The World In The Twentieth Century, Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 1999, p173</ref> commander of the [[Revolutionary Insurrectionary Army of Ukraine]] at the beginning of the 20th century. He combined horse and [[carriage]] with a machine gun in order to quickly assault targets then flee before they could properly react.\n\n==United States==\nMotorcycle ride-by killings were a common form of murder used by drug lord [[Griselda Blanco]] during her years controlling the Miami cocaine trade routes in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corben|first1=Billy|title=Griselda Blanco: So Long and Thanks for All the Cocaine|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/3b5jz8/griselda-blanco-so-long-and-thanks-for-all-the-cocaine|accessdate=24 July 2017|work=Vice|date=4 September 2012}}</ref> Blanco herself died by this method after having been shot twice in the head by a motorcyclist in a drive-by shooting in [[Medell\u00edn, Colombia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/04/godmother-cocaine-shot-dead-colombia |title='Godmother of cocaine' shot dead in Colombia |work=The Guardian |first=Richard |last=Luscombe |date=4 September 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/latest-news/article1942452.html#storylink=cpy|work=The Miami Herald|date=5 September 2012|title= The life and death of 'cocaine godmother' Griselda Blanco|author=Robles, Frances|author2=Bargent, James|last-author-amp=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/04/godmother-cocaine-shot-dead-colombia |title='Godmother of cocaine' shot dead in Colombia (Griselda Blanco, who remained under suspicion for the deaths of all three of her husbands) |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 September 2012| author=Luscombe, Richard }}</ref> Drive-by shootings are also included in the [[Ku Klux Klan]]'s ''[[modus operandi]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fontaine|first1=Smokey|title=GOOD NEWS: Victim Of KKK and Drive-By Shooting Opens Successful Restaurant|url=https://newsone.com/241747/good-news-victim-of-kkk-and-drive-by-shooting-opens-successful-restaurant/|accessdate=15 June 2017|agency=NewsOne|year=2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-carson-drive-by-shooting-20160228-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Mother and son are killed in a drive-by shooting outside a Carson home |author=Hamilton, Matt |date=28 February 2016 }}</ref> \n\nChicago [[Prohibition]]-era gangster and [[North Side Gang]] boss [[Bugs Moran]], was considered a \"pioneer\" of the drive-by shooting, with the [[Tommy gun]] being the weapon of choice. The notoriously vicious gang performed multiple shootings against their rivals, including the [[Chicago Outfit|South Side gang]] led by [[Al Capone]] and the [[Genna crime family|Genna brothers]]. \n\nDuring the [[Philadelphia crime family|Second Philadelphia Mafia War]], two warring factions fought for control of the family; one led by former alleged boss, [[John Stanfa]] and the \"[[Young Turks (disambiguation)|Young Turks]]\" led by up-and-coming gangster [[Joey Merlino]]. On August 5, 1993, Merlino survived a drive-by shooting assassination attempt by two Stanfa gunmen, taking four bullets in the leg and buttocks, while his friend and associate  Michael Ciancaglini was shot in the chest and killed.<ref name=\"deseretnews.com\">https://www.deseretnews.com/article/452913/STORIES-OF-HITS-THAT-MISSED-ARE-A-SMASH-IN-COURT.html</ref> On August 31, 1993, a drive by shooting was performed on Stanfa and his son while they were driving on the [[Schuylkill Expressway]]. Stanfa escaped uninjured and his son survived being shot in the jaw.\n\nIn 1992, the [[Mexican Mafia]] prison gang announced an edict that no [[Surenos]] sets were to commit drive-by shootings, in order to avoid police crackdowns in the [[Eastside Los Angeles|East Los Angeles]] area. Those who broke the edict were to be greenlighted for assault or even death in the California prison system. <ref>https://www-latimes-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1993-09-26-mn-39383-story.html?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&_amp=true&usqp=mq331AQCKAE%3D#aoh=15737910021709&referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.latimes.com%2Farchives%2Fla-xpm-1993-09-26-mn-39383-story.html</ref>\n\nSuch shootings are associated with [[gang violence]] in urban areas of the United States but also occur in other contexts and other countries. The tactic is also called simply a \"drive-by\".<ref name=\"drive-by-wkyc\">\n{{cite news| title = 3-year-old boy killed in drive-by shooting identified| publisher = WKYC-TV| location = Cleveland, Ohio| date = 16 September 2015| url = http://www.wkyc.com/story/news/local/cleveland/2015/09/16/3-year-old-child-woman-shot-cleveland/72343122/| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> The primary motivations for a gang-involved drive-by include intimidation, terrorization, and assassination of rival street gang members.<ref name=\"gang-epidemic\">{{cite journal | last1 = Hutson | first1 = H. Range| last2 = Anglin | first2 = Deirdre| last3 = Kyriacou | first3 = Demetrios N.| title = The Epidemic of Gang-Related Homicides in Los Angeles County From 1979 Through 1994| journal =  Journal of the American Medical Association| volume = 274| issue = 13| pages = 1031| doi = 10.1001/jama.1995.03530130037025| date = 4 October 1995}}</ref> Numerous [[hip hop]] artists have been targeted in drive-bys;<ref name=\"rappers\">{{cite web| url = http://hiphopwired.com/2013/02/01/they-shootin-10-rappers-that-were-targeted-in-drive-by-shootings/| title = They Shootin': 10 Rappers That Were Targeted in Drive-By Shootings| last = Coleman| first= C. Vernon II| date = 1 February 2013| website = HipHopWired| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> prominent rappers who were killed in such incidents include [[Tupac Shakur]],<ref name=\"pac\">{{cite web| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/tupac-shakur-dies-days-drive-by-shooting-1996-article-1.749382| title = Tupac Shakur dies days after drive-by shooting in 1996| last = Dominguez| first = Robert| date = 14 September 1996| website = Daily News|location=New York| access-date = 11 December 2015| quote = Rapper Tupac Shakur died yesterday from wounds suffered in a Las Vegas drive-by shooting, becoming a casualty of the kind of bullet-sprayed urban violence captured in his lyrics.}}</ref> [[The Notorious B.I.G.]],<ref name=\"biggie\">{{cite web| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/biggie-smalls-killed-drive-by-shooting-1997-article-1.758357| title = Biggie Smalls is killed in a drive-by shooting in 1997| last = Millner| first = Denene| date = 10 March 1997| website = Daily News|location=New York| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> [[Big L]], Smoke Dawg, and [[Mac Dre]].<ref name=\"dre\">{{cite web| url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/65810/rapper-mac-dre-killed-in-kansas-city| title = Rapper Mac Dre Killed in Kansas City| date = 2 November 2004| website = Billboard| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> Other rappers, such as [[50 Cent]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ladbible.com/entertainment/interesting-what-really-happened-when-50-cent-was-shot-nine-times-in-2000-20160706|title=What Really Happened When 50 Cent Was Shot Nine Times In 2000?|date=2016-07-06|website=www.ladbible.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> and [[Obie Trice]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/60220/rapper-obie-trice-shot-in-detroit|title=Rapper Obie Trice Shot In Detroit|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>, have survived being assaulted in drive-by shootings.\n\nIn 2015, however, Jorja Leap, an UCLA anthropologist studying [[gang culture]], pointed out how drive-by shooting tactics are being replaced by the \"walk-up shooting\" method, because murders have become more targeted and while driving, there is low accuracy in aiming.<ref>{{cite web|title=A shift in gang tactics means drive-bys are giving way to walk-ups, observers say|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=19 March 2019|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=https://homicide.latimes.com/post/drive-by-shootings/}}</ref>\n\n==Italy==\nIn [[Italy]] the circulation of firearms is low, and just over a million civilians own a firearm license,<ref>{{cite web|language=Italian|title=Quante armi ci sono in Italia? (How many firearms are there in Italy?)|date=6 February 2018|accessdate=19 March 2019|url=https://www.lastampa.it/2018/02/06/cultura/quante-armi-ci-sono-in-italia-e9Am5ZAb3cSnYCrpEtFmIJ/pagina.html|website=[[La Stampa]]}}</ref> so face-to-face shooting or threats with firearms are rare. Drive-by shooting is then common especially in professional criminal context as the statistical incidence says that almost all assaults with firearms are carried out with a running car or [[moped]]\u2014this kind of vehicle is used for reasons of better mobility in the narrow city districts. From the 1970s into the 21st century, the [[Camorra]] have been known for performing drive-by shootings during clan or gang wars, or to execute targeted murders.<ref name=\"ambrose\">{{cite book|last1=Ambrose|first1=Tom|title=The Nature of Despotism|date=2008|publisher=New Holland|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OGDuAAAAMAAJ&q=drive+by+shootings+camorra&dq=drive+by+shootings+camorra|isbn=9781847730701}}</ref>\n\nOne of the most striking episodes of a drive-by shooting in Italy was the [[Macerata shooting]], conducted against six African people by a far-right extremist, Luca Traini, using an [[Alfa Romeo 147]]. However, the attack caused no deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilmessaggero.it/primopiano/cronaca/sparatorie_macerata-3525294.html|language=Italian|title=Macerata, spari da auto in corsa, sei feriti: sono tutti di colore. Una vendetta per Pamela: bloccato un uomo avvolto nel tricolore (Macerata, drive-by shooting, six wounded: all black people. Revenge for Pamela: a man wrapped in the Italian flag arrested|date=3 February 2018|accessdate=15 March 2019|website=[[Il Messaggero]]}}</ref>\n\n==Syrian and Iraqi civil wars==\nIn the first decade of the 21st century, drive-by shootings were also used for assassinations by militants in [[Iraq]],<ref name=\"urlISIS Claims Drive-by Shooting that Killed 8 in Iraq | Asharq AL-awsat\">{{cite web |url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/1256006/isis-claims-drive-shooting-killed-8-iraq |title=ISIS Claims Drive-by Shooting that Killed 8 in Iraq &#124; Asharq AL-awsat |format= |accessdate=}}</ref> including that of the [[Waldemar Milewicz]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3693389.stm |title=Top Baghdad official shot dead: Aftermath of attack on Baghdad deputy governor: Attackers rammed the deputy governor's car and shot him dead (Gunmen have assassinated the deputy governor of Baghdad and wounded two of his bodyguards, Iraqi officials say) |work=BBC News|date=7 May 2004 |accessdate=10 August 2012}}</ref> and [[Hatem Kamil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/3970619.stm |title=Polish TV crew attacked in Iraq: Waldemar Milewicz was a well-known war correspondent (Gunmen in Iraq have killed a leading Polish journalist and his picture editor in a drive-by shooting)  |work=BBC News|date=1 November 2004 |accessdate=10 August 2012}}</ref> and in Syria.<ref name=\"urlISIS carries out drive-by shooting against rebels in Idlib (photos)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/isis-carries-out-drive-by-shooting-against-rebels-in-idlib-photos/ |title=ISIS carries out drive-by shooting against rebels in Idlib (photos) |format= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"urlBrutal Drive By Shooting Of Syrian Arab Army Troops Manning Checkpoint\">{{cite web |url=https://www.funker530.com/brutal-drive-shooting/ |title=Brutal Drive By Shooting Of Syrian Arab Army Troops Manning Checkpoint |format= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tachanka]]\n* [[Cantabrian circle]]\n* [[Caracole]]\n* [[Shoot-and-scoot]]\n* [[Hit-and-run tactics|Hit and run]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/782245.stm BBC article on 17 November shooting]\n* [http://www.iraqbodycount.org/database/ Database of Iraqi civilian casualties]\n{{portal bar|Cars}}\n[[Category:Assault tactics|Drive-by]]\n[[Category:Drive-by shootings| ]]\n[[Category:Gangs]]\n[[Category:Guerrilla warfare tactics]]\n[[Category:Urban decay]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Type of assault that typically involves the perpetrator firing a weapon from within a motor vehicle and then fleeing}}\n{{redirect|Drive-by}}\n{{For|the album by the Rollins Band|Drive by Shooting}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\nA '''drive-by shooting''' is a type of assault that usually involves the perpetrator's firing a weapon from within a [[motor vehicle]] and then fleeing.<ref name=\"hutson\">\n{{cite journal| last1 = Hutson | first1 = H. Range| last2 = Anglin | first2 = Deirdre| last3 = Pratts | first3 = Michael J. Jr.| title = Adolescents and Children Injured or Killed in Drive-By Shootings in Los Angeles| journal = New England Journal of Medicine| volume = 330| issue = 5| pages = 324\u2013327| doi = 10.1056/NEJM199402033300506| pmid = 8277953| date = 3 February 1994}}</ref> Drive-by shootings allow the perpetrator(s) to quickly strike their target and flee the scene before law enforcement is able to respond.\n\n==Historical conception==\n[[File:Makhno en 1918.JPG|220px|thumb|right|[[Nestor Makhno]] (pictured in 1918) is attributed with inventing the tactics of drive-by shooting using horses, way before motor vehicles became common]]\nThe invention of the drive-by shooting is attributed to [[Nestor Makhno]],<ref>William Henry Chamberlin, ''Russia's Iron Age'', Ayer Publishing, 1970, p201; V. Rapoport, Y. Alekseev, V. G. Treml (translated by B. Adams)</ref><ref>''High Treason: Essays on the History of the Red Army, 1918\u20131938'', Duke University Press, 1985, p68</ref><ref>Michael Malet, ''Nestor Makhno in the Russian Civil War'', Macmillan, 1982, p85</ref><ref>Steve Zaloga, Leland S. Ness, ''Red Army Handbook, 1939\u201345'', Sutton, 1998, p105</ref><ref>Leon Trotsky, ''How the Revolution Armed: The Military Writings and Speeches of Leon Trotsky'', New Park Publications, 1981, p 295</ref><ref>Edward R. Kantowicz, The Rage of Nations: The World In The Twentieth Century, Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 1999, p173</ref> commander of the [[Revolutionary Insurrectionary Army of Ukraine]] at the beginning of the 20th century. He combined horse and [[carriage]] with a machine gun in order to quickly assault targets then flee before they could properly react.\n\n==United States==\nMotorcycle ride-by killings were a common form of murder used by drug lord [[Griselda Blanco]] during her years controlling the Miami cocaine trade routes in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corben|first1=Billy|title=Griselda Blanco: So Long and Thanks for All the Cocaine|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/3b5jz8/griselda-blanco-so-long-and-thanks-for-all-the-cocaine|accessdate=24 July 2017|work=Vice|date=4 September 2012}}</ref> Blanco herself died by this method after having been shot twice in the head by a motorcyclist in a drive-by shooting in [[Medell\u00edn, Colombia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/04/godmother-cocaine-shot-dead-colombia |title='Godmother of cocaine' shot dead in Colombia |work=The Guardian |first=Richard |last=Luscombe |date=4 September 2012 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/latest-news/article1942452.html#storylink=cpy|work=The Miami Herald|date=5 September 2012|title= The life and death of 'cocaine godmother' Griselda Blanco|author=Robles, Frances|author2=Bargent, James|last-author-amp=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/04/godmother-cocaine-shot-dead-colombia |title='Godmother of cocaine' shot dead in Colombia (Griselda Blanco, who remained under suspicion for the deaths of all three of her husbands) |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 September 2012| author=Luscombe, Richard }}</ref> Drive-by shootings are also included in the [[Ku Klux Klan]]'s ''[[modus operandi]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fontaine|first1=Smokey|title=GOOD NEWS: Victim Of KKK and Drive-By Shooting Opens Successful Restaurant|url=https://newsone.com/241747/good-news-victim-of-kkk-and-drive-by-shooting-opens-successful-restaurant/|accessdate=15 June 2017|agency=NewsOne|year=2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-carson-drive-by-shooting-20160228-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Mother and son are killed in a drive-by shooting outside a Carson home |author=Hamilton, Matt |date=28 February 2016 }}</ref> \n\nChicago [[Prohibition]]-era gangster and [[North Side Gang]] boss [[Bugs Moran]], was considered a \"pioneer\" of the drive-by shooting, with the [[Tommy gun]] being the weapon of choice. The notoriously vicious gang performed multiple shootings against their rivals, including the [[Chicago Outfit|South Side gang]] led by [[Al Capone]] and the [[Genna crime family|Genna brothers]]. \n\nDuring the [[Philadelphia crime family|Second Philadelphia Mafia War]], two warring factions fought for control of the family; one led by former alleged boss, [[John Stanfa]] and the \"[[Young Turks (disambiguation)|Young Turks]]\" led by up-and-coming gangster [[Joey Merlino]]. On August 5, 1993, Merlino survived a drive-by shooting assassination attempt by two Stanfa gunmen, taking four bullets in the leg and buttocks, while his friend and associate  Michael Ciancaglini was shot in the chest and killed.<ref name=\"deseretnews.com\">https://www.deseretnews.com/article/452913/STORIES-OF-HITS-THAT-MISSED-ARE-A-SMASH-IN-COURT.html</ref> On August 31, 1993, a drive by shooting was performed on Stanfa and his son while they were driving on the [[Schuylkill Expressway]]. Stanfa escaped uninjured and his son survived being shot in the jaw.\n\nIn 1992, the [[Mexican Mafia]] prison gang announced an edict that no [[Surenos]] sets were to commit drive-by shootings, in order to avoid police crackdowns in the [[Eastside Los Angeles|East Los Angeles]] area. Those who broke the edict were to be greenlighted for assault or even death in the California prison system. <ref>https://www-latimes-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1993-09-26-mn-39383-story.html?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&_amp=true&usqp=mq331AQCKAE%3D#aoh=15737910021709&referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.latimes.com%2Farchives%2Fla-xpm-1993-09-26-mn-39383-story.html</ref>\n\nSuch shootings are associated with [[gang violence]] in urban areas of the United States but also occur in other contexts and other countries. The tactic is also called simply a \"drive-by\".<ref name=\"drive-by-wkyc\">\n{{cite news| title = 3-year-old boy killed in drive-by shooting identified| publisher = WKYC-TV| location = Cleveland, Ohio| date = 16 September 2015| url = http://www.wkyc.com/story/news/local/cleveland/2015/09/16/3-year-old-child-woman-shot-cleveland/72343122/| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> The primary motivations for a gang-involved drive-by include intimidation, terrorization, and assassination of rival street gang members.<ref name=\"gang-epidemic\">{{cite journal | last1 = Hutson | first1 = H. Range| last2 = Anglin | first2 = Deirdre| last3 = Kyriacou | first3 = Demetrios N.| title = The Epidemic of Gang-Related Homicides in Los Angeles County From 1979 Through 1994| journal =  Journal of the American Medical Association| volume = 274| issue = 13| pages = 1031| doi = 10.1001/jama.1995.03530130037025| date = 4 October 1995}}</ref> Numerous [[hip hop]] artists have been targeted in drive-bys;<ref name=\"rappers\">{{cite web| url = http://hiphopwired.com/2013/02/01/they-shootin-10-rappers-that-were-targeted-in-drive-by-shootings/| title = They Shootin': 10 Rappers That Were Targeted in Drive-By Shootings| last = Coleman| first= C. Vernon II| date = 1 February 2013| website = HipHopWired| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> prominent rappers who were killed in such incidents include [[Tupac Shakur]],<ref name=\"pac\">{{cite web| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/tupac-shakur-dies-days-drive-by-shooting-1996-article-1.749382| title = Tupac Shakur dies days after drive-by shooting in 1996| last = Dominguez| first = Robert| date = 14 September 1996| website = Daily News|location=New York| access-date = 11 December 2015| quote = Rapper Tupac Shakur died yesterday from wounds suffered in a Las Vegas drive-by shooting, becoming a casualty of the kind of bullet-sprayed urban violence captured in his lyrics.}}</ref> [[The Notorious B.I.G.]],<ref name=\"biggie\">{{cite web| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/news/crime/biggie-smalls-killed-drive-by-shooting-1997-article-1.758357| title = Biggie Smalls is killed in a drive-by shooting in 1997| last = Millner| first = Denene| date = 10 March 1997| website = Daily News|location=New York| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> [[Big L]], Smoke Dawg, and [[Mac Dre]].<ref name=\"dre\">{{cite web| url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/65810/rapper-mac-dre-killed-in-kansas-city| title = Rapper Mac Dre Killed in Kansas City| date = 2 November 2004| website = Billboard| access-date = 11 December 2015}}</ref> Other rappers, such as [[50 Cent]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ladbible.com/entertainment/interesting-what-really-happened-when-50-cent-was-shot-nine-times-in-2000-20160706|title=What Really Happened When 50 Cent Was Shot Nine Times In 2000?|date=2016-07-06|website=www.ladbible.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> and [[Obie Trice]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/60220/rapper-obie-trice-shot-in-detroit|title=Rapper Obie Trice Shot In Detroit|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>, have survived being assaulted in drive-by shootings.\n\nIn 2015, however, Jorja Leap, an UCLA anthropologist studying [[gang culture]], pointed out how drive-by shooting tactics are being replaced by the \"walk-up shooting\" method, because murders have become more targeted and while driving, there is low accuracy in aiming.<ref>{{cite web|title=A shift in gang tactics means drive-bys are giving way to walk-ups, observers say|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=19 March 2019|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=https://homicide.latimes.com/post/drive-by-shootings/}}</ref>\n\n==Italy==\nIn [[Italy]] the circulation of firearms is low, and just over a million civilians own a firearm license,<ref>{{cite web|language=Italian|title=Quante armi ci sono in Italia? (How many firearms are there in Italy?)|date=6 February 2018|accessdate=19 March 2019|url=https://www.lastampa.it/2018/02/06/cultura/quante-armi-ci-sono-in-italia-e9Am5ZAb3cSnYCrpEtFmIJ/pagina.html|website=[[La Stampa]]}}</ref> so face-to-face shooting or threats with firearms are rare. Drive-by shooting is then common especially in professional criminal context as the statistical incidence says that almost all assaults with firearms are carried out with a running car or [[moped]]\u2014this kind of vehicle is used for reasons of better mobility in the narrow city districts. From the 1970s into the 21st century, the [[Camorra]] have been known for performing drive-by shootings during clan or gang wars, or to execute targeted murders.<ref name=\"ambrose\">{{cite book|last1=Ambrose|first1=Tom|title=The Nature of Despotism|date=2008|publisher=New Holland|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OGDuAAAAMAAJ&q=drive+by+shootings+camorra&dq=drive+by+shootings+camorra|isbn=9781847730701}}</ref>\n\nOne of the most striking episodes of a drive-by shooting in Italy was the [[Macerata shooting]], conducted against six African people by a far-right extremist, Luca Traini, using an [[Alfa Romeo 147]]. However, the attack caused no deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilmessaggero.it/primopiano/cronaca/sparatorie_macerata-3525294.html|language=Italian|title=Macerata, spari da auto in corsa, sei feriti: sono tutti di colore. Una vendetta per Pamela: bloccato un uomo avvolto nel tricolore (Macerata, drive-by shooting, six wounded: all black people. Revenge for Pamela: a man wrapped in the Italian flag arrested|date=3 February 2018|accessdate=15 March 2019|website=[[Il Messaggero]]}}</ref>\n\n==Syrian and Iraqi civil wars==\nIn the first decade of the 21st century, drive-by shootings were also used for assassinations by militants in [[Iraq]],<ref name=\"urlISIS Claims Drive-by Shooting that Killed 8 in Iraq | Asharq AL-awsat\">{{cite web |url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/1256006/isis-claims-drive-shooting-killed-8-iraq |title=ISIS Claims Drive-by Shooting that Killed 8 in Iraq &#124; Asharq AL-awsat |format= |accessdate=}}</ref> including that of the [[Waldemar Milewicz]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3693389.stm |title=Top Baghdad official shot dead: Aftermath of attack on Baghdad deputy governor: Attackers rammed the deputy governor's car and shot him dead (Gunmen have assassinated the deputy governor of Baghdad and wounded two of his bodyguards, Iraqi officials say) |work=BBC News|date=7 May 2004 |accessdate=10 August 2012}}</ref> and [[Hatem Kamil]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/3970619.stm |title=Polish TV crew attacked in Iraq: Waldemar Milewicz was a well-known war correspondent (Gunmen in Iraq have killed a leading Polish journalist and his picture editor in a drive-by shooting)  |work=BBC News|date=1 November 2004 |accessdate=10 August 2012}}</ref> and in Syria.<ref name=\"urlISIS carries out drive-by shooting against rebels in Idlib (photos)\">{{cite web |url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/isis-carries-out-drive-by-shooting-against-rebels-in-idlib-photos/ |title=ISIS carries out drive-by shooting against rebels in Idlib (photos) |format= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"urlBrutal Drive By Shooting Of Syrian Arab Army Troops Manning Checkpoint\">{{cite web |url=https://www.funker530.com/brutal-drive-shooting/ |title=Brutal Drive By Shooting Of Syrian Arab Army Troops Manning Checkpoint |format= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tachanka]]\n* [[Cantabrian circle]]\n* [[Caracole]]\n* [[Shoot-and-scoot]]\n* [[Hit-and-run tactics|Hit and run]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/782245.stm BBC article on 17 November shooting]\n* [http://www.iraqbodycount.org/database/ Database of Iraqi civilian casualties]\n{{portal bar|Cars}}\n[[Category:Assault tactics|Drive-by]]\n[[Category:Drive-by shootings| ]]\n[[Category:Gangs]]\n[[Category:Guerrilla warfare tactics]]\n[[Category:Urban decay]]\n", "name_user": "Grape icecream", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed way to long because it sounds more proper", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drive-by_shooting"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Wiselius", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Samuel Iperuszoon Wiselius\n| image               = Samuel Iperusz Wiselius from dbnlorg.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| caption             = Portrait by H. W. Caspari after being [[ridder (title)|knighted]] in 1815\n| order               =\n| office              = Committee on the East-Indies <br>Trade and Possessions\n| term_start          = 1796\n| term_end            = 1801\n| predecessor         =\n| successor           =\n| birth_date          = 4 February 1769<ref name=dbnl>[http://www.dbnl.org/auteurs/auteur.php?id=wise001 Samuel Iperusz Wiselius at DBNL.org] accessed 28 September 2007</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Amsterdam]]\n| death_date          = 15 May 1845\n| death_place         = [[Amsterdam]]\n| nationality         = [[Netherlands|Dutch]]\n| party               = [[Patriottentijd]]\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| parents             = Iperus Wiselius\n| children            =\n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          = [[Leiden University]]\n| occupation          = Lawyer, writer, historian and police commissioner.\n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Samuel Iperuszoon, [[Ridder (title)|Knight]] Wiselius''' (4 February 1769 \u2013 15 May 1845) was a successful [[Netherlands|Dutch]] lawyer and a prominent [[Patriottentijd|Patriot]] and democrat, involved in the dismantling of the [[Dutch East India Company]] (VOC) and the negotiations over the [[Cape Colony|Cape]].  Wiselius was a witty, [[Voltaire|Voltairian]] spirit with political views far ahead of his time who would end his days writing dramas on Classical themes. ...<ref>Hooft, H. (1998) Patriot and Patrician: To Holland and Ceylon in the Steps of Henrik Hooft and Pieter Ondaatje, champions of the Dutch democracy, p. 187.</ref> Wiselius corresponded with nearly all the main players at the time of the [[Batavian Republic]] and it would be impossible to know that period completely without his carefully kept and neatly written correspondence. He was also a poet, historian and superintendent of the police.\n\n==Life==\n\n===Early life===\nSamuel was born in [[Amsterdam]], the only son of the oil merchant Iperus Wiselius, himself a Patriot and a captain in the [[schutterij|civic guard]], promoted to colonel in May 1787. He grew up on Nieuwezijds Kolk, probably the  oldest spot in the city centre. Samuel studied law and classics on the [[Athenaeum Illustre of Amsterdam|Athenaeum Illustre]]. In 1786 he travelled to [[Franeker]], and showed his essay on dismissing the local [[militia]] in 1650 to [[Johan Valckenaer]] and [[Theodorus van Kooten]], then progressive professors at the local University.<ref>Limburg Brouwer, P. van (1846) Het leven van Mr S.I. Wiselius, p. 24-5.</ref> Although the article went missing, the friendship remained, when the three took a prominent role in the country's future after the year 1795.\n\nSamuel had to write a new thesis and obtained his doctorate from [[Leiden University|Leiden]] in 1790. He immediately became a lawyer at the Council of Holland, which also served as a court of law. In 1791 Wiselius was the founder of the brotherhood of ''l'Infanterie des Cinq Sabres'' (\"Infantry of the Five Sabres\") at Leiden, a flirtation with [[freemasonry]].<ref>Kluit, M.E. (1953) Cornelis Felix van Maanen tot het herstel der onafhankelijkheid.</ref> ([[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]] had gained great success that year with his masonically-inspired opera ''[[The Magic Flute]]'').  Wiselius moved with his family to Amsterdam in a house at [[Prinsengracht]], across the [[Noorderkerk]]. He had full house in 1793 with three lectures for the society ''Doctrina et Amicitia'' in the [[Kalverstraat]].<ref>Wit, C.H.E. de (1965) De strijd tussen aristocratie en democratie in Nederland 1780-1848, p. 83-93.</ref> Wiselius proclaimed that the [[French Revolution]] signalled a radical new beginning. No longer was it necessary to take heed of the heavy burden of the past, he argued, but the future could be based on development and progress.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_EsKX3r0Mv4C&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&dq=%22samuel+wiselius%22&source=web&ots=eLrE3BXciX&sig=XLBuQ9SknkNFXY-MTcVPAT37PHk Dutch Culture in a European Perspective] by Willem Frijhoff, Marijke Spies, Published 2004\nUitgeverij Van Gorcum {{ISBN|90-232-3964-4}} accessed 28 September 2007</ref>\n\n===Batavian Republic===\n[[File:Wiselius.jpg|thumb|left|[[Physionotrace]] of Wiselius by [[Gilles-Louis Chr\u00e9tien]], probably made in 1797 or 1798 when Wiselius visited Paris for negotiations about Dutch ships (under non-Dutch flags), full of trade goods, which had been impounded by the French. Wiselius was bullied and returned frustrated and empty-handed.]]\n\nWhen French troops had approached the rivers [[River Rhine|Rhine]] and [[River Meuse|Meuse]] in November 1794, the Patriots started to prepare for a revolution and to stockpile weapons. The hiding place was discovered, and Jacobus van Staphorst and [[Cornelis Rudolphus Theodorus Krayenhoff]] had to leave the city to avoid being captured. The society in the Kalverstraat was closed down by the police and Wiselius, the president, had to announce the message to its members. In January 1795 Wiselius and [[Nicolaas van Staphorst]] were part of the revolutionary committee that occupied the townhall. Wiselius stood before the city government in the nearby [[Royal Palace (Amsterdam)|townhall]] on the [[Dam Square]] to state that the time had arrived for them to resign.<ref>Dunk, H.W. von der (1995) Het gebouw van de Vaderlandsche Soci\u00ebteit. In: Maandblad Amstelodamum, Jrg 82, p. 65-75.</ref> The next morning, the new leaders moved in without much ado and voted [[Rutger Jan Schimmelpenninck]] as their president. [[Stadholder William V]] escaped by boat from the beach near the Hague to England; there were no casualties and it is known as a [[velvet revolution]].\n\nTogether with [[Pieter Paulus]], Wiselius advocated an entirely new order, with more powerful central leadership. He distanced himself clearly from the [[Union of Utrecht]], which in his view was only \"a weak, barely coherent, and in many senses useless treaty violated almost daily\" (''een zwak, weinig samenhangend, veelszins nutteloos en schier dagelijks geschonden tractaat'').<ref>Vles, E.J. (2004) Pieter Paulus (1753 - 1796) Patriot en Staatsman, p. 92.</ref> The vast powers which the Provincial States (the highest authorities in the provinces) had wielded over the past two hundred years were to be reduced to those of mere clerical institutions<!--Note that \"administrative\" might erroneously be taken to mean \"governmental\" here--BD-->.<ref>Vles, E.J. (2004) Pieter Paulus (1753 - 1796) Patriot en Staatsman, p. 112.</ref>\n\nIn 1796 he was appointed one of the twenty-eight members of the Committee on the East-Indies Trade and Possessions (''Comit\u00e9 tot den Oost-Indischen Handel en Bezittingen''), along with [[Wybo Fijnje]], with whom he quarrelled two years later.  The committee had to come up with a way of dealing with the bankrupt VOC, a symbol of the [[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]'s power. The [[Dutch East India Company]] was nationalised, its so-called Outer Chambers in [[Middelburg]], [[Delft]], [[Enkhuizen]] and [[Hoorn]] closed down and its surplus employees dismissed.  In 1798 the Unitarists Wiselius, Von Liebeherr, [[Wybo Fijnje]] and [[Quint Ondaatje]] were involved in the plans of a coup by [[Daendels]]. The French ambassador [[Charles Delacroix]] was willing to help if the Dutch came up with a substantial financial reward.<ref>Hooft, H. (1998) Patriot and Patrician: To Holland and Ceylon in the Steps of Henrik Hooft and Pieter Ondaatje, champions of the Dutch democracy, p. 193.</ref> In 1801, Wiselius wrote a pamphlet making a laughing-stock of Guillelmus Titsingh, a former [[Dutch East India Company]]-administrator.<ref>Habermehl, N.D.B. (1987) Guillelmus Titsingh, een invloedrijk Amsterdams koopman uit de tweede helft van de achttiende eeuw (1733\u20131805). In: Jrb 97 Amsteldodamum, p. 81-124.</ref> As a result, Wiselius was not re-appointed as one of the nine members of the Council of Asian Possessions and Establishments (''Raad van Aziatische Bezittingen en Etablissementen''). A furious Wiselius accused his former colleagues of mismanagement.<ref>Schutte, G.J. (1974) De Nederlandse Patriotten en de koloni\u00ebn: Een onderzoek naar hun denkbeelden en optreden, 1770-1800 (''The Dutch Patriots and the colonies. An inquiry into the ideas and practices of the Dutch Enlightenment with regard to the colonies, 1770-1800. With a summary in English. pp. 121-2); Schama, S. (1987) Patriots and Liberators. Revolution in the Netherlands 1780 - 1830, p. 216; G.D. Homan, Nederland in de Napoleontische Tijd 1795-1815, p. 38.</ref> Wiselius had more respect for [[Dirk van Hogendorp (1761-1822)|Dirk van Hogendorp]], a precursor of [[Multatuli]]. In 1807 [[Herman Willem Daendels]] was sent to Batavia to prepare for the necessary changes.\n\n===Kingdom of Holland===\nThe appointment of [[Louis Bonaparte]] as King of the Netherlands led to vehement protests in 1806. Wiselius was among those refusing to offer their services to  \"Mr Bonaparte\" (''den heer Bonaparte''). Left without a post, Wiselius now devoted himself to his private interests: the history of [[Ancient Greece]] and of the city of [[Amsterdam]], and writing plays and poems, living in his country house at the borders of the River [[Vecht (Utrecht)|Vecht]].\n\nLater Wiselius was to publish the charter of 1275. He was also involved in the repairs of the dilapidated historic castle [[Muiderslot]], which was to become museum.<ref>Dunk, H.W. von der (1995) De redding van het Muiderslot. De plannen voor de bestemming van een middeleeus kasteel tot Nederlands-Historisch Museum tijdens koning Willem I. In: Maandblad Amstelodamum, Jrg 82, p. 138-168.</ref>\n\nIt was long suggested that it was Wiselius, not [[Maria Aletta Hulshoff]], who wrote the radical pamphlet entitled ''Oproeping aan het Bataafse volk'' (\"An Appeal to the Batavian People\"). Valckenaer defended her and Wiselius helped the radical Hulshoff escape to England.<ref>Joor, J. (2000) De Adelaar en het Lam. Onrust, opruiing en onwilligheid in Nederland ten tijde van het Koninkrijk Holland en de Inlijving bij het Franse Keizerrijk (1806\u20131813), p. 487-489.</ref>  In 1811, the year after, she moved to New York.\n\n===Kingdom of the Netherlands===\n[[File:Nieuweherengracht99.jpg|thumb|left|'No 99 [[Nieuwe Herengracht]] in 2007']]\n\nIn 1814, Wiselius was appointed director of the Amsterdam Police after he had refused to accept a position in [[Djakarta|Batavia]]. He preferred to stay with his children when his wife died.  In 1817, Wiselius was appointed secretary to the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences|Royal Institute of Sciences]] (KNI) as successor to [[Willem Bilderdijk]]. He had been member of the Royal Institute since 1815.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.dwc.knaw.nl/biografie/pmknaw/?pagetype=authorDetail&aId=PE00003937 |title=Samuel Wiselius Iperusz (1769 - 1845) |language=Dutch |publisher=Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences |date= |accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> In August 1824 Wiselius was visited in his recently rented house, at a prestigious canal in the [[Jewish]] neighborhood, not by [[Louis Bonaparte]] (as a long-lived legend about his house at [[Nieuwe Herengracht]] 99 would have it), but by [[Gustav IV Adolf of Sweden|Gustav IV]], the deposed and exiled king of Sweden.<ref>Wijnman, H.F. (1974) Historische Gids van Amsterdam, p. 224; Limburg Brouwer, P. van (1846) Het leven van Mr S.I. Wiselius, p. 260.</ref>  The two men discussed ''[[Revivalism#Het R\u00e9veil|Het R\u00e9veil]]'', a new, revivalist religious movement, which had started around 1810 in Switzerland.<ref>Stunt, T.C.F. (2000) From Awakening to Secession; radical evangelicals in Switzerland and Britain 1815-35). [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], (UK): T&T Clark - {{ISBN|0-567-08719-0}}</ref> Wiselius showed him the largest room of his house, with a view on the park and five enormous fixed paintings: hunting scenes by [[Jan Weenix]]. A few years before Gustav had given up his [[attic]] at the smelly [[Birsig]] in [[Basel]].\n\n[[File:Landscape with Huntsman and Dead Game 1697 Jan Weenix.jpg|thumb|''Landscape with a Huntsman and Dead Game (Allegory of the Sense of Smell)'' by [[Jan Weenix]]. This painting is in the [[National Galleries of Scotland]] in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].]]\n\nThe fixed paintings were very fashionable and appreciated in the [[Romanticism|Romantic]] era. Actually the building had always been favoured by rich and illustrious art lovers, such as [[Hendrik Grav\u00e9]] and [[Isaac de Pinto]]. In 1923, the paintings were sold in a private arrangement by the [[Order of Poor Ladies]] to the media magnate [[William Randolph Hearst]], who was travelling through Europe in search of objects for his [[Hearst Castle]] estate on the Californian coast. Since a few decades the paintings have been dispersed; two of them are in the [[Carlyle Hotel]] in New York, where Hearst lived for some time, one is in Edinburgh, one is since 1953 in the [[Allen Memorial Art Museum]] and one painting seems to be lost.\n\nIn 1835, as the head of the police, Wiselius was involved in controlling the tax revolts, organized by house owners at [[Herenmarkt]] square and in the [[Jordaan]] neighbourhood.  Afterwards he and the city mayor were heavily criticised, while sitting dozy in their chairs, after a meal.<ref>Kannegieter, Z.J. (1935) Het belastingoproer te Amsterdam in 1835. In: Amstelodamum XXXII, p. 287.</ref> Wiselius had not attended in person, but had dispatched  a commissioner instead.<ref>Kempen, A.F.J. van (1985) IJ-vorst en IJverzucht. Ambities en rivaliteit in stadsbestuur en gouvernement rondom het belastingoproer van 1835. In: Amstelodamum, p. 136-69.</ref> Wiselius resigned in 1840, but kept his position as secretary of the KNI's literary division for a few more years.\n\n==Reception==\nAfter his death his son-in-law, P. van Limburg Brouwer, a physician and writer, wrote a dull biography, but with some crucial details. The statesman [[Johan Rudolf Thorbecke|J.R. Thorbecke]] in his ''Historische Schetsen'' (\"Historical Sketches\"), published in 1860, criticised the biographer, his subject and his florid jargon. Some authors regard Wiselius as forceful, sharp-witted, animated or even overstrung. [[Simon Schama]] hardly ever has a positive opinion of Wiselius and the Patriot brotherhood, describing them as only quasi-intellectual,<ref>Schama, S. (1977) Patriots and Liberators. Revolution in the Netherlands 1780 - 1830, p. 170,</ref> and Wiselius himself as a minor figure, a [[Jacobin (politics)|Jacobin]], a [[Turncoat|renegade]]<ref>S. Schama (2007) p. 229, 231, 237, 244, 256, 273, 463, 487, 499</ref> and an over-loud, pessimistic drawing-room liberal who shirked real issues, and ended up leaving politics an embittered man.\n\n==Works (selection)==\n* ''Proeve over de verschillende regeringsvormen, in derzelver betrekking tot het maatschappelijk geluk / door S.I.Z. Wiselius (1831)\n* ''De staatkundige verlichting der Nederlanden, in een wijsgeerig-historisch tafereel geschetst : een geschrift van den jare 1793. Wiselius, Samuel Iperuszoon / 2e dr / Brest van Kempen / 1828\n* ''Geschiedenis van Oud-Griekenland / J. Del. de Sales ; in het Nederduitsch vert. en met aanm. en bijvoegzelen verm. door Samuel Iperuszoon Wiselius ; 1808\u20131817\n* ''Berijmde vertaling van het XIVde hoofdstuk van den propheet Jesaia. Wiselius, S.Iz. / Hendrik Gartman / 1813\n* ''Wederlegging van het Nader request en de zogenaamde Memorie adstructief van Mr. H. C. Cras, W. Willink en D. M. van Gelder de Neufville, aan het staats-bewind der Bataafsche Republiek, ingediend van wegen eenige participanten in de gewezen Oost-Indische Compagnie. Wiselius, Samuel Iperuszoon / Willem Holtrop / 1803\n* ''Beroep van mr. S.Iz. Wiselius, lid van den Raad der Asiatische Bezittingen en Etablissementen, op het Bataafsche volk, ter zake van den inhoud eens briefs door het wetgeevend ligchaam van het Bataafsch gemeenebest aan het staats-bewind der Bataafsche Republiek, gezonden ten geleide van de toestemming in de begroting der staats-behoeften over den jaare 1804.Wiselius, S.Iz. / W. Holtrop / 1804\n* ''Berijmde vertaling van den lierzang van Habakuk, zijnde het 3de hoofdstuk diens propheets. Wiselius, S.Iz. / H. Gartman / 1815''\n\n==Sources==\n\n* ''This article is based entirely or partially on its equivalent on Dutch Wikipedia''.\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ilab.org/db/book1091_6368.html Entry on Wiselius]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=WMUlp-ZQt_MC&pg=PA243&lpg=PA243&dq=Ondaatje+Hooft+Wiselius&source=web&ots=KB9BH7E2qT&sig=5iaBS3dGXG3u45tnDeBpn54dM84&hl=nl#PPA186,M1 Patriot and Patrian on Wiselius]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [http://www.dbnl.nl/tekst/aa__001nieu03/aa__001nieu03_0582.htm DBNL entry for Wiselius]\n* [http://www.tanap.net/content/voc/history/history_frenchperiod.htm History of the arrangement of the VOC archives]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071021165719/http://www.nationalgalleries.org/index.php/collection/online_az/4:322/results/0/17494/ One of the paintings by Jan Weenix, made for Nieuwe Herengracht 99]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [http://www.collignon.tv/ Wiselius's introduction of the word \"apekool\" (humbug or codswallop) into the Dutch language.] The word most probably originates in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]].\n* {{in lang|nl}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070825185000/http://www.nationaalarchief.nl/kind_tot_burger/html/schoolwet_cultureel1.html Wiselius handwriting]\n* {{in lang|de}} [http://www.peter-hug.ch/lexikon/1888_bild/16_0693 Entry in German Meyers Grosses Konversation Lexicon]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiselius, Samuel Iperusz.}}\n[[Category:1769 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dutch historians]]\n[[Category:Dutch lawyers]]\n[[Category:Dutch male poets]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dutch Patriots faction]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Dutch East India Company people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Amsterdam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Samuel Iperuszoon Wiselius\n| image               = Samuel Iperusz Wiselius from dbnlorg.jpg\n| image_size          = 200px\n| caption             = Portrait by H. W. Caspari after being [[ridder (title)|knighted]] in 1815\n| order               =\n| office              = Committee on the East-Indies <br>Trade and Possessions\n| term_start          = 1796\n| term_end            = 1801\n| predecessor         =\n| successor           =\n| birth_date          = 4 February 1769<ref name=dbnl>[http://www.dbnl.org/auteurs/auteur.php?id=wise001 Samuel Iperusz Wiselius at DBNL.org] accessed 28 September 2007</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Amsterdam]]\n| death_date          = 15 May 1845\n| death_place         = [[Amsterdam]]\n| nationality         = [[Netherlands|Dutch]]\n| party               = [[Patriottentijd]]\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| parents             = Iperus Wiselius\n| children            =\n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          = [[Leiden University]]\n| occupation          = Lawyer, writer, historian and police commissioner.\n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Samuel Iperuszoon, [[Ridder (title)|Knight]] Wiselius''' (4 February 1769 \u2013 15 May 1845) was a successful [[Netherlands|Dutch]] lawyer and a prominent [[Patriottentijd|Patriot]] and democrat, involved in the dismantling of the [[Dutch East India Company]] (VOC) and the negotiations over the [[Cape Colony|Cape]].  Wiselius was a witty, [[Voltaire|Voltairian]] spirit with political views far ahead of his time who would end his days writing dramas on Classical themes. ...<ref>Hooft, H. (1998) Patriot and Patrician: To Holland and Ceylon in the Steps of Henrik Hooft and Pieter Ondaatje, champions of the Dutch democracy, p. 187.</ref> Wiselius corresponded with nearly all the main players at the time of the [[Batavian Republic]] and it would be impossible to know that period completely without his carefully kept and neatly written correspondence. He was also a poet, historian and superintendent of the police.\n\n==Life==\n\n===Early life===\nSamuel was born in [[Amsterdam]], the only son of the oil merchant Iperus Wiselius, himself a Patriot and a captain in the [[schutterij|civic guard]], promoted to colonel in May 1787. He grew up on Nieuwezijds Kolk, probably the  oldest spot in the city centre. Samuel studied law and classics on the [[Athenaeum Illustre of Amsterdam|Athenaeum Illustre]]. In 1786 he travelled to [[Franeker]], and showed his essay on dismissing the local [[militia]] in 1650 to [[Johan Valckenaer]] and [[Theodorus van Kooten]], then progressive professors at the local University.<ref>Limburg Brouwer, P. van (1846) Het leven van Mr S.I. Wiselius, p. 24-5.</ref> Although the article went missing, the friendship remained, when the three took a prominent role in the country's future after the year 1795.\n\nSamuel had to write a new thesis and obtained his doctorate from [[Leiden University|Leiden]] in 1790. He immediately became a lawyer at the Council of Holland, which also served as a court of law. In 1791 Wiselius was the founder of the brotherhood of ''l'Infanterie des Cinq Sabres'' (\"Infantry of the Five Sabres\") at Leiden, a flirtation with [[freemasonry]].<ref>Kluit, M.E. (1953) Cornelis Felix van Maanen tot het herstel der onafhankelijkheid.</ref> ([[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]] had gained great success that year with his masonically-inspired opera ''[[The Magic Flute]]'').  Wiselius moved with his family to Amsterdam in a house at [[Prinsengracht]], across the [[Noorderkerk]]. He had full house in 1793 with three lectures for the society ''Doctrina et Amicitia'' in the [[Kalverstraat]].<ref>Wit, C.H.E. de (1965) De strijd tussen aristocratie en democratie in Nederland 1780-1848, p. 83-93.</ref> Wiselius proclaimed that the [[French Revolution]] signalled a radical new beginning. No longer was it necessary to take heed of the heavy burden of the past, he argued, but the future could be based on development and progress.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_EsKX3r0Mv4C&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&dq=%22samuel+wiselius%22&source=web&ots=eLrE3BXciX&sig=XLBuQ9SknkNFXY-MTcVPAT37PHk Dutch Culture in a European Perspective] by Willem Frijhoff, Marijke Spies, Published 2004\nUitgeverij Van Gorcum {{ISBN|90-232-3964-4}} accessed 28 September 2007</ref>\n\n===Batavian Republic===\n[[File:Wiselius.jpg|thumb|left|[[Physionotrace]] of Wiselius by [[Gilles-Louis Chr\u00e9tien]], probably made in 1798 when Wiselius visited Paris for negotiations about Dutch ships (under non-Dutch flags), full of trade goods, which had been impounded by the French. Wiselius was bullied and returned frustrated and empty-handed.]]\n\nWhen French troops had approached the rivers [[River Rhine|Rhine]] and [[River Meuse|Meuse]] in November 1794, the Patriots started to prepare for a revolution and to stockpile weapons. The hiding place was discovered, and Jacobus van Staphorst and [[Cornelis Rudolphus Theodorus Krayenhoff]] had to leave the city to avoid being captured. The society in the Kalverstraat was closed down by the police and Wiselius, the president, had to announce the message to its members. In January 1795 Wiselius and [[Nicolaas van Staphorst]] were part of the revolutionary committee that occupied the townhall. Wiselius stood before the city government in the nearby [[Royal Palace (Amsterdam)|townhall]] on the [[Dam Square]] to state that the time had arrived for them to resign.<ref>Dunk, H.W. von der (1995) Het gebouw van de Vaderlandsche Soci\u00ebteit. In: Maandblad Amstelodamum, Jrg 82, p. 65-75.</ref> The next morning, the new leaders moved in without much ado and voted [[Rutger Jan Schimmelpenninck]] as their president. [[Stadholder William V]] escaped by boat from the beach near the Hague to England; there were no casualties and it is known as a [[velvet revolution]].\n\nTogether with [[Pieter Paulus]], Wiselius advocated an entirely new order, with more powerful central leadership. He distanced himself clearly from the [[Union of Utrecht]], which in his view was only \"a weak, barely coherent, and in many senses useless treaty violated almost daily\" (''een zwak, weinig samenhangend, veelszins nutteloos en schier dagelijks geschonden tractaat'').<ref>Vles, E.J. (2004) Pieter Paulus (1753 - 1796) Patriot en Staatsman, p. 92.</ref> The vast powers which the Provincial States (the highest authorities in the provinces) had wielded over the past two hundred years were to be reduced to those of mere clerical institutions<!--Note that \"administrative\" might erroneously be taken to mean \"governmental\" here--BD-->.<ref>Vles, E.J. (2004) Pieter Paulus (1753 - 1796) Patriot en Staatsman, p. 112.</ref>\n\nIn 1796 he was appointed one of the twenty-eight members of the Committee on the East-Indies Trade and Possessions (''Comit\u00e9 tot den Oost-Indischen Handel en Bezittingen''), along with [[Wybo Fijnje]], with whom he quarrelled two years later.  The committee had to come up with a way of dealing with the bankrupt VOC, a symbol of the [[Ancien R\u00e9gime]]'s power. The [[Dutch East India Company]] was nationalised, its so-called Outer Chambers in [[Middelburg]], [[Delft]], [[Enkhuizen]] and [[Hoorn]] closed down and its surplus employees dismissed.  In 1798 the Unitarists Wiselius, Von Liebeherr, [[Wybo Fijnje]] and [[Quint Ondaatje]] were involved in the plans of a coup by [[Daendels]]. The French ambassador [[Charles Delacroix]] was willing to help if the Dutch came up with a substantial financial reward.<ref>Hooft, H. (1998) Patriot and Patrician: To Holland and Ceylon in the Steps of Henrik Hooft and Pieter Ondaatje, champions of the Dutch democracy, p. 193.</ref> In 1801, Wiselius wrote a pamphlet making a laughing-stock of Guillelmus Titsingh, a former [[Dutch East India Company]]-administrator.<ref>Habermehl, N.D.B. (1987) Guillelmus Titsingh, een invloedrijk Amsterdams koopman uit de tweede helft van de achttiende eeuw (1733\u20131805). In: Jrb 97 Amsteldodamum, p. 81-124.</ref> As a result, Wiselius was not re-appointed as one of the nine members of the Council of Asian Possessions and Establishments (''Raad van Aziatische Bezittingen en Etablissementen''). A furious Wiselius accused his former colleagues of mismanagement.<ref>Schutte, G.J. (1974) De Nederlandse Patriotten en de koloni\u00ebn: Een onderzoek naar hun denkbeelden en optreden, 1770-1800 (''The Dutch Patriots and the colonies. An inquiry into the ideas and practices of the Dutch Enlightenment with regard to the colonies, 1770-1800. With a summary in English. pp. 121-2); Schama, S. (1987) Patriots and Liberators. Revolution in the Netherlands 1780 - 1830, p. 216; G.D. Homan, Nederland in de Napoleontische Tijd 1795-1815, p. 38.</ref> Wiselius had more respect for [[Dirk van Hogendorp (1761-1822)|Dirk van Hogendorp]], a precursor of [[Multatuli]]. In 1807 [[Herman Willem Daendels]] was sent to Batavia to prepare for the necessary changes.\n\n===Kingdom of Holland===\nThe appointment of [[Louis Bonaparte]] as King of the Netherlands led to vehement protests in 1806. Wiselius was among those refusing to offer their services to  \"Mr Bonaparte\" (''den heer Bonaparte''). Left without a post, Wiselius now devoted himself to his private interests: the history of [[Ancient Greece]] and of the city of [[Amsterdam]], and writing plays and poems, living in his country house at the borders of the River [[Vecht (Utrecht)|Vecht]].\n\nLater Wiselius was to publish the charter of 1275. He was also involved in the repairs of the dilapidated historic castle [[Muiderslot]], which was to become museum.<ref>Dunk, H.W. von der (1995) De redding van het Muiderslot. De plannen voor de bestemming van een middeleeus kasteel tot Nederlands-Historisch Museum tijdens koning Willem I. In: Maandblad Amstelodamum, Jrg 82, p. 138-168.</ref>\n\nIt was long suggested that it was Wiselius, not [[Maria Aletta Hulshoff]], who wrote the radical pamphlet entitled ''Oproeping aan het Bataafse volk'' (\"An Appeal to the Batavian People\"). Valckenaer defended her and Wiselius helped the radical Hulshoff escape to England.<ref>Joor, J. (2000) De Adelaar en het Lam. Onrust, opruiing en onwilligheid in Nederland ten tijde van het Koninkrijk Holland en de Inlijving bij het Franse Keizerrijk (1806\u20131813), p. 487-489.</ref>  In 1811, the year after, she moved to New York.\n\n===Kingdom of the Netherlands===\n[[File:Nieuweherengracht99.jpg|thumb|left|'No 99 [[Nieuwe Herengracht]] in 2007']]\n\nIn 1814, Wiselius was appointed director of the Amsterdam Police after he had refused to accept a position in [[Djakarta|Batavia]]. He preferred to stay with his children when his wife died.  In 1817, Wiselius was appointed secretary to the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences|Royal Institute of Sciences]] (KNI) as successor to [[Willem Bilderdijk]]. He had been member of the Royal Institute since 1815.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.dwc.knaw.nl/biografie/pmknaw/?pagetype=authorDetail&aId=PE00003937 |title=Samuel Wiselius Iperusz (1769 - 1845) |language=Dutch |publisher=Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences |date= |accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> In August 1824 Wiselius was visited in his recently rented house, at a prestigious canal in the [[Jewish]] neighborhood, not by [[Louis Bonaparte]] (as a long-lived legend about his house at [[Nieuwe Herengracht]] 99 would have it), but by [[Gustav IV Adolf of Sweden|Gustav IV]], the deposed and exiled king of Sweden.<ref>Wijnman, H.F. (1974) Historische Gids van Amsterdam, p. 224; Limburg Brouwer, P. van (1846) Het leven van Mr S.I. Wiselius, p. 260.</ref>  The two men discussed ''[[Revivalism#Het R\u00e9veil|Het R\u00e9veil]]'', a new, revivalist religious movement, which had started around 1810 in Switzerland.<ref>Stunt, T.C.F. (2000) From Awakening to Secession; radical evangelicals in Switzerland and Britain 1815-35). [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], (UK): T&T Clark - {{ISBN|0-567-08719-0}}</ref> Wiselius showed him the largest room of his house, with a view on the park and five enormous fixed paintings: hunting scenes by [[Jan Weenix]]. A few years before Gustav had given up his [[attic]] at the smelly [[Birsig]] in [[Basel]].\n\n[[File:Landscape with Huntsman and Dead Game 1697 Jan Weenix.jpg|thumb|''Landscape with a Huntsman and Dead Game (Allegory of the Sense of Smell)'' by [[Jan Weenix]]. This painting is in the [[National Galleries of Scotland]] in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].]]\n\nThe fixed paintings were very fashionable and appreciated in the [[Romanticism|Romantic]] era. Actually the building had always been favoured by rich and illustrious art lovers, such as [[Hendrik Grav\u00e9]] and [[Isaac de Pinto]]. In 1923, the paintings were sold in a private arrangement by the [[Order of Poor Ladies]] to the media magnate [[William Randolph Hearst]], who was travelling through Europe in search of objects for his [[Hearst Castle]] estate on the Californian coast. Since a few decades the paintings have been dispersed; two of them are in the [[Carlyle Hotel]] in New York, where Hearst lived for some time, one is in Edinburgh, one is since 1953 in the [[Allen Memorial Art Museum]] and one painting seems to be lost.\n\nIn 1835, as the head of the police, Wiselius was involved in controlling the tax revolts, organized by house owners at [[Herenmarkt]] square and in the [[Jordaan]] neighbourhood.  Afterwards he and the city mayor were heavily criticised, while sitting dozy in their chairs, after a meal.<ref>Kannegieter, Z.J. (1935) Het belastingoproer te Amsterdam in 1835. In: Amstelodamum XXXII, p. 287.</ref> Wiselius had not attended in person, but had dispatched  a commissioner instead.<ref>Kempen, A.F.J. van (1985) IJ-vorst en IJverzucht. Ambities en rivaliteit in stadsbestuur en gouvernement rondom het belastingoproer van 1835. In: Amstelodamum, p. 136-69.</ref> Wiselius resigned in 1840, but kept his position as secretary of the KNI's literary division for a few more years.\n\n==Reception==\nAfter his death his son-in-law, P. van Limburg Brouwer, a physician and writer, wrote a dull biography, but with some crucial details. The statesman [[Johan Rudolf Thorbecke|J.R. Thorbecke]] in his ''Historische Schetsen'' (\"Historical Sketches\"), published in 1860, criticised the biographer, his subject and his florid jargon. Some authors regard Wiselius as forceful, sharp-witted, animated or even overstrung. [[Simon Schama]] hardly ever has a positive opinion of Wiselius and the Patriot brotherhood, describing them as only quasi-intellectual,<ref>Schama, S. (1977) Patriots and Liberators. Revolution in the Netherlands 1780 - 1830, p. 170,</ref> and Wiselius himself as a minor figure, a [[Jacobin (politics)|Jacobin]], a [[Turncoat|renegade]]<ref>S. Schama (2007) p. 229, 231, 237, 244, 256, 273, 463, 487, 499</ref> and an over-loud, pessimistic drawing-room liberal who shirked real issues, and ended up leaving politics an embittered man.\n\n==Works (selection)==\n* ''Proeve over de verschillende regeringsvormen, in derzelver betrekking tot het maatschappelijk geluk / door S.I.Z. Wiselius (1831)\n* ''De staatkundige verlichting der Nederlanden, in een wijsgeerig-historisch tafereel geschetst : een geschrift van den jare 1793. Wiselius, Samuel Iperuszoon / 2e dr / Brest van Kempen / 1828\n* ''Geschiedenis van Oud-Griekenland / J. Del. de Sales ; in het Nederduitsch vert. en met aanm. en bijvoegzelen verm. door Samuel Iperuszoon Wiselius ; 1808\u20131817\n* ''Berijmde vertaling van het XIVde hoofdstuk van den propheet Jesaia. Wiselius, S.Iz. / Hendrik Gartman / 1813\n* ''Wederlegging van het Nader request en de zogenaamde Memorie adstructief van Mr. H. C. Cras, W. Willink en D. M. van Gelder de Neufville, aan het staats-bewind der Bataafsche Republiek, ingediend van wegen eenige participanten in de gewezen Oost-Indische Compagnie. Wiselius, Samuel Iperuszoon / Willem Holtrop / 1803\n* ''Beroep van mr. S.Iz. Wiselius, lid van den Raad der Asiatische Bezittingen en Etablissementen, op het Bataafsche volk, ter zake van den inhoud eens briefs door het wetgeevend ligchaam van het Bataafsch gemeenebest aan het staats-bewind der Bataafsche Republiek, gezonden ten geleide van de toestemming in de begroting der staats-behoeften over den jaare 1804.Wiselius, S.Iz. / W. Holtrop / 1804\n* ''Berijmde vertaling van den lierzang van Habakuk, zijnde het 3de hoofdstuk diens propheets. Wiselius, S.Iz. / H. Gartman / 1815''\n\n==Sources==\n\n* ''This article is based entirely or partially on its equivalent on Dutch Wikipedia''.\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ilab.org/db/book1091_6368.html Entry on Wiselius]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=WMUlp-ZQt_MC&pg=PA243&lpg=PA243&dq=Ondaatje+Hooft+Wiselius&source=web&ots=KB9BH7E2qT&sig=5iaBS3dGXG3u45tnDeBpn54dM84&hl=nl#PPA186,M1 Patriot and Patrian on Wiselius]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [http://www.dbnl.nl/tekst/aa__001nieu03/aa__001nieu03_0582.htm DBNL entry for Wiselius]\n* [http://www.tanap.net/content/voc/history/history_frenchperiod.htm History of the arrangement of the VOC archives]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071021165719/http://www.nationalgalleries.org/index.php/collection/online_az/4:322/results/0/17494/ One of the paintings by Jan Weenix, made for Nieuwe Herengracht 99]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [http://www.collignon.tv/ Wiselius's introduction of the word \"apekool\" (humbug or codswallop) into the Dutch language.] The word most probably originates in [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]].\n* {{in lang|nl}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070825185000/http://www.nationaalarchief.nl/kind_tot_burger/html/schoolwet_cultureel1.html Wiselius handwriting]\n* {{in lang|de}} [http://www.peter-hug.ch/lexikon/1888_bild/16_0693 Entry in German Meyers Grosses Konversation Lexicon]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiselius, Samuel Iperusz.}}\n[[Category:1769 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dutch historians]]\n[[Category:Dutch lawyers]]\n[[Category:Dutch male poets]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dutch Patriots faction]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Dutch East India Company people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Amsterdam]]\n", "name_user": "Taksen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBatavian Republic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Wiselius"}
