te|ascent}} This data is from the [http://www.alpine-club.org.uk/hi/ Himalayan Index] and is not always correct. In particular it is not clear if [[Batura Sar]] has really had four ascents or only three.\n# {{note|batura}} Sometimes called Batura I.\n# {{note|ultar}} Sometimes called Ultar II or Bojohagur Duanasir II.\n# {{note|sangemarname}} Also known as Sang-e-Marmar (or Sangemarmar), and sometimes referred to by locals as Marble Peak.\n# {{note|sangemarht}} The heights given for this peak vary between 6949m and 7050m.\n# {{note|bulimotinht}} This elevation is approximate.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Batura Muztagh}}\n*[http://www.alpine-club.org.uk/hi/ Himalayan Index]\n*[http://blankonthemap.free.fr/1_accueil/index.php?code=20050505 A clickable map of the Batura Muztagh]\n*[http://www.viewfinderpanoramas.org/dem3.html#himalayas DEM files for the Himalaya] (Corrected versions of SRTM data; look for the \"Batura Sar\" tile)\n\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of the Karakoram]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain range\n| name=Batura Muztagh<br>{{nq|\u0628\u062a\u0648\u0631\u0627 \u0645\u0648\u0632 \u062a\u0627\u063a}}\n|native_name=\n| photo=Batura_muztagh.jpg\n| photo_caption=Aerial view of part of the Batura Muztagh from the southeast\n| country=Pakistan\n| state_type=Region\n| region=Gilgit District\n| parent=Karakoram|border=| border1=\n| geology=| period= | orogeny=\n| area_km2= | length_km=| length_orientation=\n| width_km= | width_orientation=\n| highest=Batura Sar\n| elevation_m=7795 \n|coordinates = {{coord|36|30|36|N|74|31|37|E|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| map= | map_caption=\n}}\nThe '''Batura Muztagh''' ({{Lang-ur|\u0628\u062a\u0648\u0631\u0627 \u0645\u0648\u0632 \u062a\u0627\u063a}}) mountains are a sub-range of the [[Karakoram]] [[mountain range]]. They are located in [[Gojal Valley|Gojal valley]] in the [[Hunza District|Hun